# Default bar chart



<pre class="mcode">
p <- ggplot(mtcars, aes(factor(cyl)))
p <-  p + geom_bar()

plotly::ggplotly(p)
</pre>

# Transparent colour

Use NA for a completely transparent colour.

<pre class="mcode">
p <- ggplot(mtcars, aes(factor(cyl)))
p <-  p + geom_bar(fill = NA, colour = "#00abff")

plotly::ggplotly(p)
</pre>

# Colour discrete plot

Colouring scales differ depending on whether a discrete or continuous variable is being mapped.

For example, when mapping fill to a factor variable, a discrete colour scale is used.


<pre class="mcode">
p <-  ggplot(mtcars, aes(factor(cyl), fill = factor(vs))) + geom_bar()

plotly::ggplotly(p)
</pre>

# Colour continuous plot

When mapping fill to continuous variable a continuous colour scale is used.

<pre class="mcode">
p <-    
 ggplot(faithfuld, aes(waiting, eruptions)) +
  geom_raster(aes(fill = density))
  
plotly::ggplotly(p)
</pre>

# Plots that use only colour, not fill

Some geoms only use the colour aesthetic but not the fill aesthetic (e.g. `geom_point()` or `geom_line()`).

<pre class="mcode">
p <- ggplot(economics, aes(x = date, y = unemploy))
p <-  p + geom_line()

plotly::ggplotly(p)
</pre>

To make elements transparent use `alpha`; where value 0 means they will be fully transparent, and value 1 means no transparent at all.

<pre class="mcode">
df <- data.frame(x = rnorm(5000), y = rnorm(5000))

p  <- ggplot(df, aes(x,y))
p <-  p + geom_point(alpha = 0.5)

plotly::ggplotly(p)
</pre>
